text: melissa: Hey there! Any chance you were able to jam on this yesterday?
<!here|@here> 10min trend refresh is independent of the actual API to get the trend data from GAE. The API call is usually 50-60ms response time.

<@U1S5GKTHQ|dimitry> uploaded a file: <https://uncorked.slack.com/files/dimitry/F5T0923M2/pasted_image_at_2017_06_13_09_32_am.png|Pasted image at 2017-06-13, 9:32 AM> and commented: The cron job service takes 6-10 mins as seen here. We have 47 countries and for each, we get list of trend items and then details about each trend item (up to 20), so altogether a max of 987 API calls.

text: I believe this used to be faster back in the day, but def. slowed down.

One solution: improve the script by implementing timeouts for each API call. the downside is if any of the 20 trend detail calls fail, that whole country won’t get a refreshed list (or we can skip that specific trend?). the upside is limiting the max execution time and no more 500s.

Another solution: reimplement this completely. I was thinking of using Google Cloud Functions BUT I’m getting the following when trying to access that panel in GAE:

> To use Cloud Functions with this project, contact a project owner to enable billing
This is for `gweb-uncorked-3PR` project. I thought our client had done some special magic to this GAE project to lift the quotas and “unlock” it?
Oh hm.
Will find out.
My question was mostly a sanity check. The internal tools that track the pixel 2 prerelease detected three long running trend update service requests
And I wasn't sure if when those happened if something was happening server side
Seems like maybe the time out needs to be adjusted on the client side
No, I can try and devote some time to it today.

<@U2H61EJSG> let me know if this makes sense / looks good to you.
This is a video example
and this is a GIF example

```{
    "notification_type": "live_case_update",
    "media_type": "app_image",
    "app_image": {
        "image_url": "<http://www.example.com/>",
        "image_description": "Check out this gif.",
        "filetype": "gif",
        "width":100,
        "height":100
    },
    "links": [{
        "link_title": "Just the one link",
        "link_url": "<http://www.example.com>"
    }],
    "locale": "en_ca",
    "notification_title": "This is the push notification title",
    "notification_message": "This is the push notification message",
    "generator": [1, 2],
    "in_app_title": "In-app title",
    "in_app_message": "In-app message",
    "generations": "new"
}
```
I'm showing an example where there is one link or more than one links in each of these. If there are no links, it will be an empty array
Also, filetype is just the three letter extension. I think on your end, you can ignore if it is not gif
This is perfect! Thank you!!
<@U2670DYLE>  Quick question, what is returned if ‘media_type’ is not set?
media_type will be set to "none, and key/values for "app_image" and "youtube_video" will be absent in the json.
perfect
Is ‘google.sent_time’ still included like it was previously?

There should be 4 fields for title and message; 2 for notification and 2 for in-app (unless the ‘same as notification content’ box is checked

I'll edit the snippets above, so as not to confuse things.
Thank you!
